Applicant shows a clear increase in portfolio value over a measureable span which is always a plus.  Also has a nice background with a variety of experience so we don't feel we need to pigeon hole her in an evaluation.  Her education is also very solid with her Masters from a Business School.  

A lot of the accomplishments listed on the resume were a bit broad with limited results.  Even though results were listed on the end of the most recent job it feels like there should be something measureable for each one for us to ask her and evaluate progress.  Also a lot of the skills she listed were very common for the job which I feel should not be used in a professional resume.  Kind of disappointed regarding the lack of details regarding her previous job before her current one.  I feel there should be more information there which makes me feel like she may be a one hit wonder from her current employer and her success may not translate well to us.

One of the main pro's is that the resume is extremely professional and lists numbered results instead of broad accomplishments.  Having a number of running projects which may have a positive impact on her current employer shows she always has something on the other side ready.  Also the overall improvement and retention rates are impressive even if they are not long term sustainable increases.  

Main Con's are that a lot of the projects she is claiming credit for have not been seen out long term.  It is entirely possible these seemingly good projects go south and both us and the company she worked for are stuck operating sub-optimally.  She has also only done her previous job for one employer and as such may have been a big fish in a smaller pond and may be over performing due to gravely poor performance of those that came before her.  Seems to also have some other things going on outside of work with the PTA so she may not be able to commit as much to as as we would like.
